Git Commands and Explanations
Initialize a new Git repository:

git init
Creates a new Git repository in the current directory.

Add files to the staging area:

git add <file>
Stages specific files for the next commit.

Check the status of your repository:

git status
Shows the current status of the working directory and staging area.

Remove a file from the staging area:

git rm --cached <file>
Un-stages a file while keeping it in your working directory.

Commit staged changes:

git commit -m "message"
Commits the staged changes to the repository with a descriptive message.

Restore working directory files:

git restore <file>
Reverts changes in the working directory for a specified file.

Configure your user name globally:

git config --global user.name "<git-username>"
Sets your global username for Git commits.

Configure your email globally:

git config --global user.email "<email address>"
Sets your global email for Git commits.

View commit history:

git log
Displays the commit history in reverse chronological order.

List all branches:

git branch
Lists all the branches in your repository.

Create and switch to a new branch:

git checkout -b dev
Creates a new branch named dev and switches to it.

View a concise commit history:

git log --oneline
Shows the commit history in a simplified format.

